#Text=Tugal Caris
#Text=Tugal Caris ( late 16th century – 1665 or 1666 ) , also spelled Carris or Cariste , was a 17th-century French sculptor and architect .
#Text=Biography
#Text=Caris was born in the late sixteenth century or early seventeenth century .
#Text=In 1630 , he was associated in a market with Jean Martinet for the purchase of 600 carts of stones from the Couldre and Bootz quarries at Changé .
#Text=He then lived in Laval .
#Text=This purchase did not concern the construction of altarpieces .
#Text=He was the husband of Jeanne Barais , probably the sister of Catherine Barais , wife of the architect Michel Bellier . [ 1 ]
#Text=They had several children , including a son Jacques Caris who moved to Nantes where , after having been associated with his father , he became an architect .
#Text=Origins
#Text=Marie Bellier , wife of Antoine Agenyau , architect . [ 2 ]
#Text=Michel Bellier , [ 3 ] architect , husband of Catherine Barais . [ 4 ]
#Text=Louise Bellier , wife of Philippe Bault , lawyer at Rennes
#Text=Guillaume Bellier
#Text=Renée Bellier , wife of Jean Martinet , architect
#Text=Olivier Martinet , architect
#Text=Lavallois Rededos
#Text=His first known altarpiece is that of Vaiges , now missing , built in 1634 .
#Text=He can probably also be attributed the realization of the altar Saint-Denis at Saint-Denis-du-Maine in 1632 , and the altar Saint-Pierre at Nuillé-sur-Ouette in 1633 .
#Text=From 1634 to 1636 , he erected the altarpiece [ 5 ] of the Saint-Sauveur Abbey of Redon . [ 6 ]
#Text=Caris is also attributed the two side altars of this church , but which do not date from the same period .
#Text=In June 1636 , he was in Laval where he contested the quality of the marble ordered from Étienne Arnoul , and asked for an expertise from Pierre Corbineau and Jean Martinet .
#Text=After Redon 's realization , he made an altarpiece at the church of the Cordeliers of Rennes in 1636 , then from 1637 to 1639 , the high altar of the Saint-Vénérand church of Laval . [ 7 ]
#Text=Around 1639 , he made the main altarpiece of the Tréguier Cathedral . [ 8 ]
#Text=At the same time , he raised two altarpieces at Bonchamp-lès-Laval .
#Text=In 1640 , he realized the high altar and the altar of the Rosary of the Saint-Martin church of Châtillon-sur-Colmont .
#Text=The reredos of the right altar , representing the Virgin Mary , is composed of small medallions .
#Text=In each medallion , a mystery of the Rosary is represented as a scene .
#Text=Altarpiece of the Rosary of the Church of Chatillon-sur-Colmont .
#Text=Main altar and altarpiece ( church of Brée ) , attributed to Tugal Caris .
#Text=Architect at Rennes and Nantes
#Text=After the lavallois reredos , he moved to architecture , and was entrusted with the realization of the façade of the Rennes Cathedral . [ 9 ]
#Text=He built the large portal and part of the towers from 1640 to 1654 .
#Text=He then became entrepreneur du Palace of Rennes , [ 10 ]
#Text=whose construction he resumed after Jacques Corbineau .
#Text=He signed with the community of the city of Rennes on 28 April 1640 for the " continuation of work on the side of the Cordeliers " .

column1: #Text=He then lived in Rennes where he directed the most important works .
#Text=In 1642 he built two side altarpieces and the main altar [ 11 ] of Availles-sur-Seiche [ 12 ] as well as that of Rannée [ 13 ]
#Text=He is also attributed the altarpiece of the high altar [ 14 ] of the church of Tinténiac .

#Text=Nevertheless , the work carried out at the Palace of Parliament of Brittany was deemed not to conform to the plans and specifications drawn up by Salomon de Brosse in 1618 , and was destroyed in 1647 by order of the Parliament of Brittany .
#Text=Caris was dispossessed of his office for the benefit of Pierre Corbineau .
#Text=In 1648 he left Rennes [ 15 ] for Nantes where he built a convent and private mansions .

#Text=It is possible that he was at this time between Nantes , Rennes where he managed the cathedral site until 1654 , and Gaël where he raised the altarpiece of the high altar in 1650-1651. He seems to leave Rennes in 1654 definitively , the cathedral site was also taken over by Pierre Corbineau .
#Text=The construction of the Cathedral in Rennes was eventful : Tugal Caris must start again in 1651 in granite instead of the tufa initially chosen .
#Text=According to Léon Palustre , Tugal Caris would have led the work to the cornice on the first floor .

#Text=After him , from 1654 to 1678 , Pierre Corbineau completed the superposition of the three orders and placed the coat of arms of Louis XIV above the immense window in the façade of the monument .
#Text=Then François Huguet [ 16 ] cleared the two towers , gave them two independent floors , and in 1703 put the finishing touches to this work .
#Text=He brought the levels to their current height of 48 metres and added on the pediment at the top of the façade
#Text=Louis XIV 's motto : Nec pluribus impar , the unparalleled .

#Text=Caris completeed the rededo of the altar Notre-Dame-de-Pitié in one of the chapels [ 17 ] of the Nantes Cathedral circa 1656 , the same year he was awarded the contract for the cathedral 's works [ 18 ]
#Text=Il meurt à Nantes en 1665 ou 1666 . [ 19 ]
